description.text: This thing was made with Tinkercad. Edit it online https://www.tinkercad.com/things/fWNRBN15upS

I am new to quadcopter designs & was not sure what size I wanted my quadcopter to be. After looking at several designs, I decided to come up with a parametric Arm design so I could easily change some key dimensions of the arm & see how it looked visually put together. This is not a remix, but did use the wire channel idea from the Peon230 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:629338. I made the ledges on each side of the arms 8 sided which has worked well for me in other designs adding strength with less plastic & in this case giving a channel for the wires to lay in also. There is also an option to make the arms flat in case you do not need that channel.

There are quite a few dimensions you can change for this design & I have included a PDF file showing the variables that may not be obvious from the description in the openscad file. You can use this as visual aid to see how different length arms, locations & rotations affect your design. Once you have it the way you want it, you can set the PartView variable to 0 to display your arm for printing.

The arms generated by this could be used for Tricopters, Hexacopters or Octocopters. Some small changes would need to be made to the code to visually show the other style drones.

The frame I am using for the visual on these arms is a modification to the BumbleBee Quad http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:745092 .

As you can see from the screen capture, this will show you whether your props interfere with each other or be in the camera view. If they interfere, you can just change the length of the arms, the size of the props, rotation of the front and/or back arms or the location of where the arms are located on the frame.

description.text:
A Raspberry Pi case in the shape of that most classic video game console.  
The cartridge slot is also conveniently sized to hold an SD card.

Print the base, the top and the face plate.  For maximum accuracy, print the top and the base in black, and the face plate in brown ABS or PLA, or possibly Laywoo D3.  
(The whole case .stl is just there for illustration, it probably won't print well!)  
Angle the Pi into the base, power connector first, then tilt the USB/Ethernet ports down until they are secure in their openings.  
Slide the face plate into the slot in the base, then put the top on and enjoy some retro gaming action!  
The power plug hole is sized for a low-prifile micro USB.  If poeple want a larger hole, I can make another version, or you can modify the .SCAD file if you so desire.  
I don't use the analog video or headphone jacks, but I will upload another faceplate file that has openings for them.

description.text:
This is a Makerbot Cupcake, reprap, Thing-o-matic, etc compatible version of the Highly awersom Jetty version of the Makerbot firmware. The menus have been reorganized to be a little more uncluttered. A few other features above the Jetty firmware have been included. Machine presets for steps per mm settings. Updated SD card library to fix a few bugs. Use X+/X- to navigate to the other menus. If you have Gen4 electronics and have either a makerbot interface or built your own makerbot interface with a more readily available 20x4 display, then this firmware is for you. Features includes
Selectable Display width 16,20 or 24.
Selectable Zmm per revolution. So if you have a cupcake with gen4 electronics, a thing-o-matic steps per rev will be incorrect. Now you can set this to what you want.
Pause on next Z. Pauses the build on the next Z movement.
Pause and free move. Allows you to re-position the head and continue printing from there.
Bouncy SD File name.
Extrude countdown.
Key Testing. And more. Sorry Snake is currently disabled due to Rom size constraints. Source is a at https://github.com/johnnyfp/G3Firmware

To install.
Either rename your existing 3.1Hex file and replace with the file in the ZIP or create a new entry in the firmware.xml file to point to the file in the ZIP. Flash. Enjoy.

description.text:
A dock for the HTC G1 (Android phone). The hole in the middle is the proper size for the cable that came with the phone in the box, so if you use a different USB cable, you'll need to resize the hole.
Printed one, and it took an hour and fifty three (1:53) to print, with the included gcode.  Previous version printed with major warping in the front, so on this one the base is a bit smaller.  I also tried the hairdryer trick to prevent warping.  For the first ~10 minutes I pointed a hairdryer set to high heat, low air at the build.  This prevented all of the warping in the first layers and I feel was comparable to a heated build chamber.  It helped alot to prevent warping in the build.  The raft adhered to the part so well that I couldn't get it off (suggestions are welcome for the removal of pesky rafts).

-1. Download STL
  • Skeinforge to taste.
  • Print one.
    1.5 Clean off raft and bits.
  • Stuff cable in. May require assistance with exacto knife to enlarge hole a little bit as it is pretty tight right now.
